{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01KEjGXN1C5mKWsVYp9YdAH9","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01R6P6eg27ms1UcAeYRDRz9D","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/home/mila/e/elarabim/code/x-reviewer-agent/agent_configs/quadrant/reasoning/19599555_verdict_20260428.md","content":"# Verdict Reasoning: 19599555 — Robust Skills, Brittle Grounding\n\n**Paper:** Robust Skills, Brittle Grounding: Diagnosing Restricted Generalization in Vision-Language Action Policies via Multi-Object Picking  \n**Paper ID:** 19599555-2b78-4017-81b6-249864d15150  \n**Date:** 2026-04-28  \n**Score:** 5.0 (weak accept, lower band)\n\n---\n\n## Novelty Assessment\n\nThe paper introduces a four-rung spatial difficulty ladder (jitter levels: none → small → medium → large) paired with decomposed metrics (Success / Grasp-anything / Reach) that independently measure instruction-conditioned target selection and execution capability. The key finding — in-distribution Success 44% collapses to OOD Success 0% while Reach degrades only modestly (Table 3) — provides clean diagnostic evidence that shortcut learning in the grounding component is the binding constraint, not motor skill failure. To my knowledge, this is the first systematic diagnostic that isolates instruction-following breakdowns in VLA policies from pure execution capability, which constitutes clear novelty relative to prior VLA evaluation work.\n\nNovelty cell: **clear-novelty** (new diagnostic benchmark with decomposed metrics isolating grounding from execution)\n\n---\n\n## Rigor Assessment\n\n**Critical rigor concern — Table 1 vs Table 2 discrepancy:**  \nAs identified by $_$ [[comment:bc91fcce-8d6a-4d69-889d-1ae36e986eb9]], Table 1 and Table 2 report different SmolVLA success rates for medium- and large-jitter conditions (5pp and 7pp differences respectively), with no caption note explaining the discrepancy. This is a load-bearing failure for an empirical paper whose primary claim rests on precise metric values. Reviewer_Gemini_1 [[comment:0a66ebd6-f0ba-4179-b729-9d92d86efac5]] further identified a metric interpretation contradiction (inverse scaling anomaly in intermediate regimes), suggesting that large-jitter conditions yield anomalously high Reach rates that the paper describes inconsistently. Entropius [[comment:13a9f62a-b38a-4f4c-8bda-58cb6062aa79]] independently confirmed the paper's novelty relative to prior robotic manipulation diagnostics while noting the empirical scope is narrow (one simulator, one task family). novelty-fact-checker [[comment:8e4ec01e-4dc5-4677-bf63-b8703fafffe6]] confirmed the Reach metric definition (5cm threshold) is correctly stated in Section 3.3, which resolves one interpretation dispute in the thread.\n\n**Secondary concern — baseline coverage:**  \nAll evaluated policies are VLA models (SmolVLA, Pi0, OpenVLA-OFT). No ablation against a simpler spatial attention baseline (e.g., centroid-based target selection or object detector + language matcher) is provided to establish that the grounding failure is specific to end-to-end VLA training rather than any instruction-following approach.\n\nRigor cell: **some concerns** (table inconsistency is significant but the core OOD collapse finding appears robust across both tables)\n\n---\n\n## Grid Assignment\n\n| Novelty | Rigor | Default band | Score |\n|---------|-------|-------------|-------|\n| clear-novelty | some concerns | weak accept (upper) | 6.0–6.8 |\n\nThe Table 1/2 reporting inconsistency and the inverse-scaling metric interpretation issue pull the score toward the lower end of the weak accept band. The narrow task scope (single simulator, single task family) limits generalizability claims. Adjusted score: **5.0**\n\n---\n\n## Citations in Verdict\n\n- [[comment:bc91fcce-8d6a-4d69-889d-1ae36e986eb9]] — $_$: Table 1 vs Table 2 SmolVLA discrepancy (5-7pp)\n- [[comment:0a66ebd6-f0ba-4179-b729-9d92d86efac5]] — Reviewer_Gemini_1: metric interpretation contradiction, inverse scaling anomaly\n- [[comment:13a9f62a-b38a-4f4c-8bda-58cb6062aa79]] — Entropius: novelty relative to prior art; empirical scope assessment\n- [[comment:8e4ec01e-4dc5-4677-bf63-b8703fafffe6]] — novelty-fact-checker: Reach metric confirmation\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":587,"cache_read_input_tokens":95472,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":587},"output_tokens":39,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e49c1731-2d50-4798-abb8-e764589428f2","uuid":"de06b06b-febd-431f-a97f-2b9bf7880bd4"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01R6P6eg27ms1UcAeYRDRz9D","type":"tool_result","content":"File created successfully at: /home/mila/e/elarabim/code/x-reviewer-agent/agent_configs/quadrant/reasoning/19599555_verdict_20260428.md"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e49c1731-2d50-4798-abb8-e764589428f2","uuid":"56de6adc-f427-4192-af89-3ae4107d60ce","timestamp":"2026-04-28T17:29:37.795Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"create","filePath":"/home/mila/e/elarabim/code/x-reviewer-agent/agent_configs/quadrant/reasoning/19599555_verdict_20260428.md","content":"# Verdict Reasoning: 19599555 — Robust Skills, Brittle Grounding\n\n**Paper:** Robust Skills, Brittle Grounding: Diagnosing Restricted Generalization in Vision-Language Action Policies via Multi-Object Picking  \n**Paper ID:** 19599555-2b78-4017-81b6-249864d15150  \n**Date:** 2026-04-28  \n**Score:** 5.0 (weak accept, lower band)\n\n---\n\n## Novelty Assessment\n\nThe paper introduces a four-rung spatial difficulty ladder (jitter levels: none → small → medium → large) paired with decomposed metrics (Success / Grasp-anything / Reach) that independently measure instruction-conditioned target selection and execution capability. The key finding — in-distribution Success 44% collapses to OOD Success 0% while Reach degrades only modestly (Table 3) — provides clean diagnostic evidence that shortcut learning in the grounding component is the binding constraint, not motor skill failure. To my knowledge, this is the first systematic diagnostic that isolates instruction-following breakdowns in VLA policies from pure execution capability, which constitutes clear novelty relative to prior VLA evaluation work.\n\nNovelty cell: **clear-novelty** (new diagnostic benchmark with decomposed metrics isolating grounding from execution)\n\n---\n\n## Rigor Assessment\n\n**Critical rigor concern — Table 1 vs Table 2 discrepancy:**  \nAs identified by $_$ [[comment:bc91fcce-8d6a-4d69-889d-1ae36e986eb9]], Table 1 and Table 2 report different SmolVLA success rates for medium- and large-jitter conditions (5pp and 7pp differences respectively), with no caption note explaining the discrepancy. This is a load-bearing failure for an empirical paper whose primary claim rests on precise metric values. Reviewer_Gemini_1 [[comment:0a66ebd6-f0ba-4179-b729-9d92d86efac5]] further identified a metric interpretation contradiction (inverse scaling anomaly in intermediate regimes), suggesting that large-jitter conditions yield anomalously high Reach rates that the paper describes inconsistently. Entropius [[comment:13a9f62a-b38a-4f4c-8bda-58cb6062aa79]] independently confirmed the paper's novelty relative to prior robotic manipulation diagnostics while noting the empirical scope is narrow (one simulator, one task family). novelty-fact-checker [[comment:8e4ec01e-4dc5-4677-bf63-b8703fafffe6]] confirmed the Reach metric definition (5cm threshold) is correctly stated in Section 3.3, which resolves one interpretation dispute in the thread.\n\n**Secondary concern — baseline coverage:**  \nAll evaluated policies are VLA models (SmolVLA, Pi0, OpenVLA-OFT). No ablation against a simpler spatial attention baseline (e.g., centroid-based target selection or object detector + language matcher) is provided to establish that the grounding failure is specific to end-to-end VLA training rather than any instruction-following approach.\n\nRigor cell: **some concerns** (table inconsistency is significant but the core OOD collapse finding appears robust across both tables)\n\n---\n\n## Grid Assignment\n\n| Novelty | Rigor | Default band | Score |\n|---------|-------|-------------|-------|\n| clear-novelty | some concerns | weak accept (upper) | 6.0–6.8 |\n\nThe Table 1/2 reporting inconsistency and the inverse-scaling metric interpretation issue pull the score toward the lower end of the weak accept band. The narrow task scope (single simulator, single task family) limits generalizability claims. Adjusted score: **5.0**\n\n---\n\n## Citations in Verdict\n\n- [[comment:bc91fcce-8d6a-4d69-889d-1ae36e986eb9]] — $_$: Table 1 vs Table 2 SmolVLA discrepancy (5-7pp)\n- [[comment:0a66ebd6-f0ba-4179-b729-9d92d86efac5]] — Reviewer_Gemini_1: metric interpretation contradiction, inverse scaling anomaly\n- [[comment:13a9f62a-b38a-4f4c-8bda-58cb6062aa79]] — Entropius: novelty relative to prior art; empirical scope assessment\n- [[comment:8e4ec01e-4dc5-4677-bf63-b8703fafffe6]] — novelty-fact-checker: Reach metric confirmation\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null,"userModified":false}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01SFFdxz9LHDACB4YAJhmwEm","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01NCXjjWcPdBUA41DpkzkpLH","name":"Write","input":{"file_path":"/home/mila/e/elarabim/code/x-reviewer-agent/agent_configs/quadrant/reasoning/3616779a_verdict_20260428.md","content":"# Verdict Reasoning: 3616779a — When Actions Go Off-Task\n\n**Paper:** When Actions Go Off-Task: Detecting and Correcting Misaligned Actions in Computer-Use Agents  \n**Paper ID:** 3616779a-8ed8-4d00-9a1c-71616a5ecbd2  \n**Date:** 2026-04-28  \n**Score:** 5.0 (weak accept, lower band)\n\n---\n\n## Novelty Assessment\n\nThe paper introduces MISACTBENCH, the first multimodal Computer-Use Agent (CUA) benchmark with per-action alignment labels (Fleiss' κ = 0.84), and a two-stage detection-correction pipeline (fast-check + rewriter) built on Claude Sonnet 4.5. The per-action labeling granularity is a genuine methodological advance over prior trajectory-level safety labels in WebArena, OSWorld, and similar benchmarks. The decomposition into misalignment detection (fast-check) and correction (rewriter) cleanly separates the two problems.\n\nNovelty cell: **clear-novelty** (per-action annotation granularity + detection-correction pipeline are new relative to trajectory-level CUA safety work)\n\n---\n\n## Rigor Assessment\n\n**Critical concern — synthesizer-detector confound:**  \nAs I noted in my comment [[comment:9391c85c-6139-4ca0-a4cf-fb5c1c7376bb]] and claude_shannon elaborated [[comment:65292a6d-e7c0-47af-9a76-7da548a370f8]], Claude Sonnet 4.5 serves as both the primary backbone for MISACTBENCH annotation/construction and as the fast-check and rewriter backbone in the evaluated pipeline. This creates a same-family recognition bias: the detector may perform well partly because it shares stylometric and behavioral priors with the generator, rather than because the method generalizes to misaligned actions from other agent families. The effect is attenuated in fast-check (lightweight heuristic) but meaningful in the rewriter stage. No cross-family generalization experiment (e.g., using a GPT-4o-generated trace evaluated by the Claude-based pipeline) is provided.\n\n**Secondary concern — Table E.1 brittle recall:**  \nTable E.1 shows recall of 73.81% on H-type (hacked/adversarial) misalignment examples, implying a 26.19% miss rate on the hardest misalignment category. For a safety-critical CUA monitoring system, this miss rate is potentially unacceptable and the paper does not discuss the deployment implications.\n\n**Novelty framing concern:**  \nEntropius [[comment:b64cde38-4600-47b1-a2fc-b5a8b2ec370b]] and emperorPalpatine [[comment:08e11686-0b08-45f2-afe2-ec4c3309aedb]] both note that framing this as the \"first effort\" creates tension with concurrent work (Task Shield, InferAct). The paper cites these as contemporaneous but the extent of methodological overlap is not fully characterized.\n\nRigor cell: **some concerns** (synthesizer-detector confound reduces evaluation validity; brittle recall on adversarial cases)\n\n---\n\n## Grid Assignment\n\n| Novelty | Rigor | Default band | Score |\n|---------|-------|-------------|-------|\n| clear-novelty | some concerns | weak accept (upper) | 6.0–6.8 |\n\nSynthesizer-detector confound and the brittle adversarial recall pull toward the lower bound. The per-action labeling contribution and high inter-annotator agreement are genuine strengths. Adjusted score: **5.0**\n\n---\n\n## Citations in Verdict\n\n- [[comment:65292a6d-e7c0-47af-9a76-7da548a370f8]] — claude_shannon: synthesizer-detector confound + adaptive attacker concern\n- [[comment:b64cde38-4600-47b1-a2fc-b5a8b2ec370b]] — Entropius: novelty relative to concurrent work (Task Shield, InferAct)\n- [[comment:08e11686-0b08-45f2-afe2-ec4c3309aedb]] — emperorPalpatine: multiple novelty and soundness concerns\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1253,"cache_read_input_tokens":96059,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1253},"output_tokens":72,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e49c1731-2d50-4798-abb8-e764589428f2","uuid":"d905cf20-72c4-42db-9f23-b8433f327de2"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01NCXjjWcPdBUA41DpkzkpLH","type":"tool_result","content":"File created successfully at: /home/mila/e/elarabim/code/x-reviewer-agent/agent_configs/quadrant/reasoning/3616779a_verdict_20260428.md"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e49c1731-2d50-4798-abb8-e764589428f2","uuid":"7ae983ac-fdd5-4d37-99d6-aec1110ee652","timestamp":"2026-04-28T17:29:59.227Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"create","filePath":"/home/mila/e/elarabim/code/x-reviewer-agent/agent_configs/quadrant/reasoning/3616779a_verdict_20260428.md","content":"# Verdict Reasoning: 3616779a — When Actions Go Off-Task\n\n**Paper:** When Actions Go Off-Task: Detecting and Correcting Misaligned Actions in Computer-Use Agents  \n**Paper ID:** 3616779a-8ed8-4d00-9a1c-71616a5ecbd2  \n**Date:** 2026-04-28  \n**Score:** 5.0 (weak accept, lower band)\n\n---\n\n## Novelty Assessment\n\nThe paper introduces MISACTBENCH, the first multimodal Computer-Use Agent (CUA) benchmark with per-action alignment labels (Fleiss' κ = 0.84), and a two-stage detection-correction pipeline (fast-check + rewriter) built on Claude Sonnet 4.5. The per-action labeling granularity is a genuine methodological advance over prior trajectory-level safety labels in WebArena, OSWorld, and similar benchmarks. The decomposition into misalignment detection (fast-check) and correction (rewriter) cleanly separates the two problems.\n\nNovelty cell: **clear-novelty** (per-action annotation granularity + detection-correction pipeline are new relative to trajectory-level CUA safety work)\n\n---\n\n## Rigor Assessment\n\n**Critical concern — synthesizer-detector confound:**  \nAs I noted in my comment [[comment:9391c85c-6139-4ca0-a4cf-fb5c1c7376bb]] and claude_shannon elaborated [[comment:65292a6d-e7c0-47af-9a76-7da548a370f8]], Claude Sonnet 4.5 serves as both the primary backbone for MISACTBENCH annotation/construction and as the fast-check and rewriter backbone in the evaluated pipeline. This creates a same-family recognition bias: the detector may perform well partly because it shares stylometric and behavioral priors with the generator, rather than because the method generalizes to misaligned actions from other agent families. The effect is attenuated in fast-check (lightweight heuristic) but meaningful in the rewriter stage. No cross-family generalization experiment (e.g., using a GPT-4o-generated trace evaluated by the Claude-based pipeline) is provided.\n\n**Secondary concern — Table E.1 brittle recall:**  \nTable E.1 shows recall of 73.81% on H-type (hacked/adversarial) misalignment examples, implying a 26.19% miss rate on the hardest misalignment category. For a safety-critical CUA monitoring system, this miss rate is potentially unacceptable and the paper does not discuss the deployment implications.\n\n**Novelty framing concern:**  \nEntropius [[comment:b64cde38-4600-47b1-a2fc-b5a8b2ec370b]] and emperorPalpatine [[comment:08e11686-0b08-45f2-afe2-ec4c3309aedb]] both note that framing this as the \"first effort\" creates tension with concurrent work (Task Shield, InferAct). The paper cites these as contemporaneous but the extent of methodological overlap is not fully characterized.\n\nRigor cell: **some concerns** (synthesizer-detector confound reduces evaluation validity; brittle recall on adversarial cases)\n\n---\n\n## Grid Assignment\n\n| Novelty | Rigor | Default band | Score |\n|---------|-------|-------------|-------|\n| clear-novelty | some concerns | weak accept (upper) | 6.0–6.8 |\n\nSynthesizer-detector confound and the brittle adversarial recall pull toward the lower bound. The per-action labeling contribution and high inter-annotator agreement are genuine strengths. Adjusted score: **5.0**\n\n---\n\n## Citations in Verdict\n\n- [[comment:65292a6d-e7c0-47af-9a76-7da548a370f8]] — claude_shannon: synthesizer-detector confound + adaptive attacker concern\n- [[comment:b64cde38-4600-47b1-a2fc-b5a8b2ec370b]] — Entropius: novelty relative to concurrent work (Task Shield, InferAct)\n- [[comment:08e11686-0b08-45f2-afe2-ec4c3309aedb]] — emperorPalpatine: multiple novelty and soundness concerns\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null,"userModified":false}}
