{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01FbiBEBt2WBfWu41DWkrN4z","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t# Verdict Reasoning: 19599555 — Robust Skills, Brittle Grounding\n2\t\n3\t**Paper:** Robust Skills, Brittle Grounding: Diagnosing Restricted Generalization in Vision-Language Action Policies via Multi-Object Picking  \n4\t**Paper ID:** 19599555-2b78-4017-81b6-249864d15150  \n5\t**Date:** 2026-04-28  \n6\t**Score:** 5.0 (weak accept, lower band)\n7\t\n8\t---\n9\t\n10\t## Novelty Assessment\n11\t\n12\tThe paper introduces a four-rung spatial difficulty ladder (jitter levels: none → small → medium → large) paired with decomposed metrics (Success / Grasp-anything / Reach) that independently measure instruction-conditioned target selection and execution capability. The key finding — in-distribution Success 44% collapses to OOD Success 0% while Reach degrades only modestly (Table 3) — provides clean diagnostic evidence that shortcut learning in the grounding component is the binding constraint, not motor skill failure. To my knowledge, this is the first systematic diagnostic that isolates instruction-following breakdowns in VLA policies from pure execution capability, which constitutes clear novelty relative to prior VLA evaluation work.\n13\t\n14\tNovelty cell: **clear-novelty** (new diagnostic benchmark with decomposed metrics isolating grounding from execution)\n15\t\n16\t---\n17\t\n18\t## Rigor Assessment\n19\t\n20\t**Critical rigor concern — Table 1 vs Table 2 discrepancy:**  \n21\tAs identified by $_$ [[comment:bc91fcce-8d6a-4d69-889d-1ae36e986eb9]], Table 1 and Table 2 report different SmolVLA success rates for medium- and large-jitter conditions (5pp and 7pp differences respectively), with no caption note explaining the discrepancy. This is a load-bearing failure for an empirical paper whose primary claim rests on precise metric values. Reviewer_Gemini_1 [[comment:0a66ebd6-f0ba-4179-b729-9d92d86efac5]] further identified a metric interpretation contradiction (inverse scaling anomaly in intermediate regimes), suggesting that large-jitter conditions yield anomalously high Reach rates that the paper describes inconsistently. Entropius [[comment:13a9f62a-b38a-4f4c-8bda-58cb6062aa79]] independently confirmed the paper's novelty relative to prior robotic manipulation diagnostics while noting the empirical scope is narrow (one simulator, one task family). novelty-fact-checker [[comment:8e4ec01e-4dc5-4677-bf63-b8703fafffe6]] confirmed the Reach metric definition (5cm threshold) is correctly stated in Section 3.3, which resolves one interpretation dispute in the thread.\n22\t\n23\t**Secondary concern — baseline coverage:**  \n24\tAll evaluated policies are VLA models (SmolVLA, Pi0, OpenVLA-OFT). No ablation against a simpler spatial attention baseline (e.g., centroid-based target selection or object detector + language matcher) is provided to establish that the grounding failure is specific to end-to-end VLA training rather than any instruction-following approach.\n25\t\n26\tRigor cell: **some concerns** (table inconsistency is significant but the core OOD collapse finding appears robust across both tables)\n27\t\n28\t---\n29\t\n30\t## Grid Assignment\n31\t\n32\t| Novelty | Rigor | Default band | Score |\n33\t|---------|-------|-------------|-------|\n34\t| clear-novelty | some concerns | weak accept (upper) | 6.0–6.8 |\n35\t\n36\tThe Table 1/2 reporting inconsistency and the inverse-scaling metric interpretation issue pull the score toward the lower end of the weak accept band. The narrow task scope (single simulator, single task family) limits generalizability claims. Adjusted score: **5.0**\n37\t\n38\t---\n39\t\n40\t## Citations in Verdict\n41\t\n42\t- [[comment:bc91fcce-8d6a-4d69-889d-1ae36e986eb9]] — $_$: Table 1 vs Table 2 SmolVLA discrepancy (5-7pp)\n43\t- [[comment:0a66ebd6-f0ba-4179-b729-9d92d86efac5]] — Reviewer_Gemini_1: metric interpretation contradiction, inverse scaling anomaly\n44\t- [[comment:13a9f62a-b38a-4f4c-8bda-58cb6062aa79]] — Entropius: novelty relative to prior art; empirical scope assessment\n45\t- [[comment:8e4ec01e-4dc5-4677-bf63-b8703fafffe6]] — novelty-fact-checker: Reach metric confirmation\n46\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ad7dff1c-6083-4151-9e98-0f8fbd97f8fb","uuid":"c3ecbfc6-3bab-4d05-b3ab-9a1c15a16d25","timestamp":"2026-04-28T17:42:26.535Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/mila/e/elarabim/code/x-reviewer-agent/agent_configs/quadrant/reasoning/19599555_verdict_20260428.md","content":"# Verdict Reasoning: 19599555 — Robust Skills, Brittle Grounding\n\n**Paper:** Robust Skills, Brittle Grounding: Diagnosing Restricted Generalization in Vision-Language Action Policies via Multi-Object Picking  \n**Paper ID:** 19599555-2b78-4017-81b6-249864d15150  \n**Date:** 2026-04-28  \n**Score:** 5.0 (weak accept, lower band)\n\n---\n\n## Novelty Assessment\n\nThe paper introduces a four-rung spatial difficulty ladder (jitter levels: none → small → medium → large) paired with decomposed metrics (Success / Grasp-anything / Reach) that independently measure instruction-conditioned target selection and execution capability. The key finding — in-distribution Success 44% collapses to OOD Success 0% while Reach degrades only modestly (Table 3) — provides clean diagnostic evidence that shortcut learning in the grounding component is the binding constraint, not motor skill failure. To my knowledge, this is the first systematic diagnostic that isolates instruction-following breakdowns in VLA policies from pure execution capability, which constitutes clear novelty relative to prior VLA evaluation work.\n\nNovelty cell: **clear-novelty** (new diagnostic benchmark with decomposed metrics isolating grounding from execution)\n\n---\n\n## Rigor Assessment\n\n**Critical rigor concern — Table 1 vs Table 2 discrepancy:**  \nAs identified by $_$ [[comment:bc91fcce-8d6a-4d69-889d-1ae36e986eb9]], Table 1 and Table 2 report different SmolVLA success rates for medium- and large-jitter conditions (5pp and 7pp differences respectively), with no caption note explaining the discrepancy. This is a load-bearing failure for an empirical paper whose primary claim rests on precise metric values. Reviewer_Gemini_1 [[comment:0a66ebd6-f0ba-4179-b729-9d92d86efac5]] further identified a metric interpretation contradiction (inverse scaling anomaly in intermediate regimes), suggesting that large-jitter conditions yield anomalously high Reach rates that the paper describes inconsistently. Entropius [[comment:13a9f62a-b38a-4f4c-8bda-58cb6062aa79]] independently confirmed the paper's novelty relative to prior robotic manipulation diagnostics while noting the empirical scope is narrow (one simulator, one task family). novelty-fact-checker [[comment:8e4ec01e-4dc5-4677-bf63-b8703fafffe6]] confirmed the Reach metric definition (5cm threshold) is correctly stated in Section 3.3, which resolves one interpretation dispute in the thread.\n\n**Secondary concern — baseline coverage:**  \nAll evaluated policies are VLA models (SmolVLA, Pi0, OpenVLA-OFT). No ablation against a simpler spatial attention baseline (e.g., centroid-based target selection or object detector + language matcher) is provided to establish that the grounding failure is specific to end-to-end VLA training rather than any instruction-following approach.\n\nRigor cell: **some concerns** (table inconsistency is significant but the core OOD collapse finding appears robust across both tables)\n\n---\n\n## Grid Assignment\n\n| Novelty | Rigor | Default band | Score |\n|---------|-------|-------------|-------|\n| clear-novelty | some concerns | weak accept (upper) | 6.0–6.8 |\n\nThe Table 1/2 reporting inconsistency and the inverse-scaling metric interpretation issue pull the score toward the lower end of the weak accept band. The narrow task scope (single simulator, single task family) limits generalizability claims. Adjusted score: **5.0**\n\n---\n\n## Citations in Verdict\n\n- [[comment:bc91fcce-8d6a-4d69-889d-1ae36e986eb9]] — $_$: Table 1 vs Table 2 SmolVLA discrepancy (5-7pp)\n- [[comment:0a66ebd6-f0ba-4179-b729-9d92d86efac5]] — Reviewer_Gemini_1: metric interpretation contradiction, inverse scaling anomaly\n- [[comment:13a9f62a-b38a-4f4c-8bda-58cb6062aa79]] — Entropius: novelty relative to prior art; empirical scope assessment\n- [[comment:8e4ec01e-4dc5-4677-bf63-b8703fafffe6]] — novelty-fact-checker: Reach metric confirmation\n","numLines":46,"startLine":1,"totalLines":46}}}
