{"type":"system","subtype":"task_notification","task_id":"a9d10b60211829d52","tool_use_id":"toolu_01WrTKarhsfFzAATyPR7zvnw","status":"completed","output_file":"","summary":"Review paper: Perplexity Cannot Always Tell Right from Wrong","usage":{"total_tokens":51744,"tool_uses":2,"duration_ms":31294},"uuid":"8fa55de9-409b-4fd7-88d7-3b6064f2533d","session_id":"ad7dff1c-6083-4151-9e98-0f8fbd97f8fb"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01WrTKarhsfFzAATyPR7zvnw","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Here is the structured technical review based on a full read of the paper.\n\n---\n\n**Review: \"Perplexity Cannot Always Tell Right from Wrong\"**\n\n**Strengths:**\n\n1. The paper's central theoretical contribution (Proposition 3.2 / Corollary 3.3) is cleanly stated and proved: leveraging Pasten et al. (2025)'s CPE continuity theorem, the authors demonstrate that any model confident and correct on a sufficiently long sequence must admit a nearby sequence with arbitrarily low log-perplexity that it nonetheless mis-copies. The proof in Appendix A is rigorous and the derivation of the required threshold n' (Eq. 17) is explicit.\n\n2. The iso-perplexity curve analysis (Sec. 4.2, Eq. 11) provides a concrete, analytically derived bound on the accuracy surplus a model must achieve to justify increased confidence under perplexity-based model selection — a practically useful diagnostic contribution beyond the existence proof.\n\n**Concerns:**\n\n1. **(Strongest) Scope is narrow and heavily assumption-laden.** The theoretical results (Prop. 3.2, Cor. 3.3) apply exclusively to CPE decoder-only Transformers on bitstring copy tasks under greedy decoding. The extension to stochastic sampling (Sec. 3.3, Prop. 3.6) is only an informal proof and yields weak bounds (failure probability ≤ Nγ). Real-world perplexity misuse — the paper's motivating concern — operates over diverse tasks, vocabularies, and sampling regimes not covered by these results.\n\n2. **(Sec. 4.2) Iso-perplexity framework assumes homogeneous confidence.** The model in Eq. 10 assigns identical confidence (1−γ) to every prediction, which the authors themselves acknowledge \"may well not be a value of γ that fits an observed perplexity/accuracy pair\" in practice (p. 7). The analytic curves are therefore derived under conditions that the paper's own empirical setup violates, undermining the direct connection between theory and Figure 3.\n\n3. **(Sec. 4.3–4.5) Single parity-task experiment with limited statistical reporting.** The empirical validation uses one Transformer checkpoint trajectory on one task (parity, sizes ≤16 IID, size 128 OOD). No error bars, no seeds reported, no comparison against alternative metrics, and the OOD regime (training on ≤16 bits, evaluating at 128) is a severe distributional shift by design rather than a naturalistic one. Pearson r=0.31 OOD is presented as validating the hypothesis, but with ~50 checkpoints on a single run this is statistically underpowered.\n\n4. **(Sec. 5) No alternative or remedy proposed.** The paper explicitly states \"we do not offer an alternative to perplexity.\" Given the narrow scope of the proved failure modes, the practical takeaway is limited to a cautionary message without actionable guidance.\n\n**Recommendations:**\n\n- Extend empirical validation to at least one additional task and report statistics over multiple seeds.\n- Clarify in the abstract and introduction that the proofs are restricted to CPE Transformers on copy tasks; the current framing implies broader generality.\n- Strengthen Sec. 3.3 with a formal (not informal) proof, or remove the stochastic extension and scope claims accordingly.\n\n**Overall:** The paper makes a technically sound, if narrow, theoretical contribution to the known limitations of perplexity. The proof is correct but relies heavily on prior work (Pasten et al., 2025), the empirical validation is minimal, and the practical scope is limited. This situates the paper in the weak-accept range — a useful technical note but not a full-scale research contribution.\n\n---\n\n**Novelty cell:** incremental\n**Rigor cell:** some concerns\n**Proposed score:** 5.0"},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a9d10b60211829d52 (use SendMessage with to: 'a9d10b60211829d52' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 52597\ntool_uses: 2\nduration_ms: 31297</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ad7dff1c-6083-4151-9e98-0f8fbd97f8fb","uuid":"3574e749-8545-4101-b240-8e120488e24e","timestamp":"2026-04-28T17:45:23.959Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"You are helping a peer review agent analyze a research paper for the ICML 2026 Agent Review Competition on the Koala Science platform.\n\n**Paper:** \"Perplexity Cannot Always Tell Right from Wrong\"\n**Paper ID:** 4de49ebc-3e95-4555-bee7-c6c1d4f04900\n**Domain:** NLP/Deep-Learning/Theory\n**ArXiv ID:** (unknown)\n**PDF URL:** https://koala.science/storage/pdfs/4de49ebc-3e95-4555-bee7-c6c1d4f04900.pdf\n\n**Your task:** Fetch and read the paper PDF. Then write a structured technical review (220-320 words) covering:\n- **Strengths:** 1-2 concrete contributions\n- **Concerns:** 2-4 evidence-backed issues (lead with strongest), each anchored to a page/section/table/equation\n- **Recommendations:** Actionable suggestions tied to concerns\n- **Overall:** Situate relative to verdict band (clear-reject / weak-reject / weak-accept / strong-accept / spotlight)\n\nAlso provide:\n- **Novelty cell:** breakthrough / clear-novelty / incremental / re-derived / no-novelty\n- **Rigor cell:** solid / some concerns / major gaps\n- **Proposed score:** 0.0-10.0 in 0.5 steps (based on the grid: clear-novelty+solid→7.5-8.5, clear-novelty+some concerns→6.0-6.8, incremental+solid→5.0-5.8, incremental+some concerns→4.0-4.8)\n\nFocus on: benchmark design, leakage, statistical rigor, whether perplexity as an evaluation metric has known issues that the paper documents correctly, claim-evidence alignment.\n\nReturn the full review text plus novelty/rigor assessment and proposed score. Do NOT post anything - just analyze and return the text.","agentId":"a9d10b60211829d52","agentType":"general-purpose","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Here is the structured technical review based on a full read of the paper.\n\n---\n\n**Review: \"Perplexity Cannot Always Tell Right from Wrong\"**\n\n**Strengths:**\n\n1. The paper's central theoretical contribution (Proposition 3.2 / Corollary 3.3) is cleanly stated and proved: leveraging Pasten et al. (2025)'s CPE continuity theorem, the authors demonstrate that any model confident and correct on a sufficiently long sequence must admit a nearby sequence with arbitrarily low log-perplexity that it nonetheless mis-copies. The proof in Appendix A is rigorous and the derivation of the required threshold n' (Eq. 17) is explicit.\n\n2. The iso-perplexity curve analysis (Sec. 4.2, Eq. 11) provides a concrete, analytically derived bound on the accuracy surplus a model must achieve to justify increased confidence under perplexity-based model selection — a practically useful diagnostic contribution beyond the existence proof.\n\n**Concerns:**\n\n1. **(Strongest) Scope is narrow and heavily assumption-laden.** The theoretical results (Prop. 3.2, Cor. 3.3) apply exclusively to CPE decoder-only Transformers on bitstring copy tasks under greedy decoding. The extension to stochastic sampling (Sec. 3.3, Prop. 3.6) is only an informal proof and yields weak bounds (failure probability ≤ Nγ). Real-world perplexity misuse — the paper's motivating concern — operates over diverse tasks, vocabularies, and sampling regimes not covered by these results.\n\n2. **(Sec. 4.2) Iso-perplexity framework assumes homogeneous confidence.** The model in Eq. 10 assigns identical confidence (1−γ) to every prediction, which the authors themselves acknowledge \"may well not be a value of γ that fits an observed perplexity/accuracy pair\" in practice (p. 7). The analytic curves are therefore derived under conditions that the paper's own empirical setup violates, undermining the direct connection between theory and Figure 3.\n\n3. **(Sec. 4.3–4.5) Single parity-task experiment with limited statistical reporting.** The empirical validation uses one Transformer checkpoint trajectory on one task (parity, sizes ≤16 IID, size 128 OOD). No error bars, no seeds reported, no comparison against alternative metrics, and the OOD regime (training on ≤16 bits, evaluating at 128) is a severe distributional shift by design rather than a naturalistic one. Pearson r=0.31 OOD is presented as validating the hypothesis, but with ~50 checkpoints on a single run this is statistically underpowered.\n\n4. **(Sec. 5) No alternative or remedy proposed.** The paper explicitly states \"we do not offer an alternative to perplexity.\" Given the narrow scope of the proved failure modes, the practical takeaway is limited to a cautionary message without actionable guidance.\n\n**Recommendations:**\n\n- Extend empirical validation to at least one additional task and report statistics over multiple seeds.\n- Clarify in the abstract and introduction that the proofs are restricted to CPE Transformers on copy tasks; the current framing implies broader generality.\n- Strengthen Sec. 3.3 with a formal (not informal) proof, or remove the stochastic extension and scope claims accordingly.\n\n**Overall:** The paper makes a technically sound, if narrow, theoretical contribution to the known limitations of perplexity. The proof is correct but relies heavily on prior work (Pasten et al., 2025), the empirical validation is minimal, and the practical scope is limited. This situates the paper in the weak-accept range — a useful technical note but not a full-scale research contribution.\n\n---\n\n**Novelty cell:** incremental\n**Rigor cell:** some concerns\n**Proposed score:** 5.0"}],"totalDurationMs":31297,"totalTokens":52597,"totalToolUseCount":2,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":32207,"cache_read_input_tokens":19468,"output_tokens":919,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":32207},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[{"input_tokens":3,"output_tokens":919,"cache_read_input_tokens":19468,"cache_creation_inpu