{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01QRZEMisfqfW5JbRkqApvLB","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Here is the structured technical review based on a full read of the paper:\n\n---\n\n**DAJ: Data-Reweighted LLM Judge for Test-Time Scaling in Code Generation**\n\n**Strengths**\n\n1. **Principled distribution-shift framing.** The paper cleanly identifies three distinct sources of mismatch (easy–hard imbalance, task distribution shift, trajectory mismatch) and proposes a unified bi-level optimization framework that addresses all three simultaneously without hand-crafted heuristics. Grounding the reweighting factors in the meta-set construction (Appendix C) rather than separate modules is elegant.\n\n2. **Strong empirical results at small scale.** DAJ achieves 84.7% on LiveCodeBench and 35.9% on BigCodeBench-Hard (Tables 1–2) using a 1.7B backbone, outperforming substantially larger baselines (DeepSeek GRM at 16B). Cross-policy evaluation across four base models (Table 3) strengthens generalization claims.\n\n**Concerns**\n\n1. **Compute-unfair comparison against zero-shot baselines (Table 2, Sec. 5.2).** The primary headline claim—\"outperforming o4-mini (high) by 7.6 points\"—conflates a multi-sample Best-of-N system against a single-pass zero-shot model. DAJ uses 4–8 sampled candidates plus R=8 voting rounds with an additional trained judge; o4-mini (high) uses one pass. The effective compute budget per problem is not equalized, and no FLOPs-matched or token-budget-matched comparison is provided. This is the paper's most significant methodological gap.\n\n2. **Meta-set data contamination risk (Appendix A).** The upper-level meta set for LiveCodeBench uses problems released between 2024-08-01 and 2025-02-01, while the test set uses problems from 2025-02-01 to 2025-05-01. This temporal gap is only 6 months. For BigCodeBench, the top-20%-hardest tasks define the meta set, measured by pass rates of the same policy models used in evaluation—this circular difficulty estimation is not analyzed for leakage.\n\n3. **Ablation incompleteness (Table 4b).** The reinforcement-learning ablation (Table 4b) only reports GRPO with \"no reweighting\" and \"domain reweighting.\" Instance-table and instance-net results are absent for RL, preventing a full comparison of reweighting granularity under the best-performing training objective. The paper's main model uses GRPO+domain reweighting, yet the preference-optimization results show instance-net is best (Table 4a)—this inconsistency is unaddressed.\n\n4. **One-step unrolling approximation not validated (Sec. 4, Eq. 7–8).** The bi-level optimization uses a one-step unrolling approximation. No convergence analysis, sensitivity study, or ablation over unrolling depth is provided to justify that this approximation does not degrade performance relative to a tighter solver.\n\n**Recommendations**\n\n- Add a compute-controlled comparison: fix total inference tokens/FLOPs across methods and report accuracy under the budget constraint.\n- Report instance-net and instance-table results under GRPO to complete Table 4b.\n- Provide an ablation over unrolling depth (1 vs. 2–3 steps) to validate the approximation.\n- Clarify the BigCodeBench difficulty-split procedure to rule out circular evaluation.\n\n**Overall**\n\nThe work addresses a real problem with a technically sound framework and achieves impressive empirical numbers. The headline comparison against zero-shot models is misleading without compute normalization, and the ablation table is incomplete. Falls in the weak-accept range pending those clarifications.\n\n---\n\n**Novelty cell:** incremental (data reweighting applied to a new setting; the bi-level optimization mechanics are from prior work)\n\n**Rigor cell:** some concerns (compute-unfair baselines, incomplete ablation, unrolling approximation unvalidated)\n\n**Proposed score:** 5.5"},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: adb4fa89ebef418e5 (use SendMessage with to: 'adb4fa89ebef418e5' to continue this agent)\n<usage>total_tokens: 63819\ntool_uses: 2\nduration_ms: 33712</usage>"}]}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"ad7dff1c-6083-4151-9e98-0f8fbd97f8fb","uuid":"95bf5f53-ad58-445b-abf8-42880589983f","timestamp":"2026-04-28T17:45:29.521Z","tool_use_result":{"status":"completed","prompt":"You are helping a peer review agent analyze a research paper for the ICML 2026 Agent Review Competition on the Koala Science platform.\n\n**Paper:** \"DAJ: Data-Reweighted LLM Judge for Test-Time Scaling in Code Generation\"\n**Paper ID:** d68449ac-2313-481d-a204-b4668e69e345\n**Domain:** NLP/Deep-Learning/Optimization\n**PDF URL:** https://koala.science/storage/pdfs/d68449ac-2313-481d-a204-b4668e69e345.pdf\n\n**Your task:** Fetch and read the paper PDF. Then write a structured technical review (220-320 words) covering:\n- **Strengths:** 1-2 concrete contributions\n- **Concerns:** 2-4 evidence-backed issues (lead with strongest), each anchored to a page/section/table/equation\n- **Recommendations:** Actionable suggestions tied to concerns\n- **Overall:** Situate relative to verdict band\n\nAlso provide:\n- **Novelty cell:** breakthrough / clear-novelty / incremental / re-derived / no-novelty\n- **Rigor cell:** solid / some concerns / major gaps\n- **Proposed score:** 0.0-10.0 in 0.5 steps\n\nFocus on: LLM judge bias (judge-model self-preference), test-time scaling methodology, baseline fairness, whether the reweighting approach addresses root causes or patches symptoms, statistical rigor.\n\nReturn the full review text plus novelty/rigor assessment and proposed score. Do NOT post anything - just analyze and return the text.","agentId":"adb4fa89ebef418e5","agentType":"general-purpose","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Here is the structured technical review based on a full read of the paper:\n\n---\n\n**DAJ: Data-Reweighted LLM Judge for Test-Time Scaling in Code Generation**\n\n**Strengths**\n\n1. **Principled distribution-shift framing.** The paper cleanly identifies three distinct sources of mismatch (easy–hard imbalance, task distribution shift, trajectory mismatch) and proposes a unified bi-level optimization framework that addresses all three simultaneously without hand-crafted heuristics. Grounding the reweighting factors in the meta-set construction (Appendix C) rather than separate modules is elegant.\n\n2. **Strong empirical results at small scale.** DAJ achieves 84.7% on LiveCodeBench and 35.9% on BigCodeBench-Hard (Tables 1–2) using a 1.7B backbone, outperforming substantially larger baselines (DeepSeek GRM at 16B). Cross-policy evaluation across four base models (Table 3) strengthens generalization claims.\n\n**Concerns**\n\n1. **Compute-unfair comparison against zero-shot baselines (Table 2, Sec. 5.2).** The primary headline claim—\"outperforming o4-mini (high) by 7.6 points\"—conflates a multi-sample Best-of-N system against a single-pass zero-shot model. DAJ uses 4–8 sampled candidates plus R=8 voting rounds with an additional trained judge; o4-mini (high) uses one pass. The effective compute budget per problem is not equalized, and no FLOPs-matched or token-budget-matched comparison is provided. This is the paper's most significant methodological gap.\n\n2. **Meta-set data contamination risk (Appendix A).** The upper-level meta set for LiveCodeBench uses problems released between 2024-08-01 and 2025-02-01, while the test set uses problems from 2025-02-01 to 2025-05-01. This temporal gap is only 6 months. For BigCodeBench, the top-20%-hardest tasks define the meta set, measured by pass rates of the same policy models used in evaluation—this circular difficulty estimation is not analyzed for leakage.\n\n3. **Ablation incompleteness (Table 4b).** The reinforcement-learning ablation (Table 4b) only reports GRPO with \"no reweighting\" and \"domain reweighting.\" Instance-table and instance-net results are absent for RL, preventing a full comparison of reweighting granularity under the best-performing training objective. The paper's main model uses GRPO+domain reweighting, yet the preference-optimization results show instance-net is best (Table 4a)—this inconsistency is unaddressed.\n\n4. **One-step unrolling approximation not validated (Sec. 4, Eq. 7–8).** The bi-level optimization uses a one-step unrolling approximation. No convergence analysis, sensitivity study, or ablation over unrolling depth is provided to justify that this approximation does not degrade performance relative to a tighter solver.\n\n**Recommendations**\n\n- Add a compute-controlled comparison: fix total inference tokens/FLOPs across methods and report accuracy under the budget constraint.\n- Report instance-net and instance-table results under GRPO to complete Table 4b.\n- Provide an ablation over unrolling depth (1 vs. 2–3 steps) to validate the approximation.\n- Clarify the BigCodeBench difficulty-split procedure to rule out circular evaluation.\n\n**Overall**\n\nThe work addresses a real problem with a technically sound framework and achieves impressive empirical numbers. The headline comparison against zero-shot models is misleading without compute normalization, and the ablation table is incomplete. Falls in the weak-accept range pending those clarifications.\n\n---\n\n**Novelty cell:** incremental (data reweighting applied to a new setting; the bi-level optimization mechanics are from prior work)\n\n**Rigor cell:** some concerns (compute-unfair baselines, incomplete ablation, unrolling approximation unvalidated)\n\n**Proposed score:** 5.5"}],"totalDurationMs":33712,"totalTokens":63819,"totalToolUseCount":2,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":43461,"cache_read_input_tokens":19384,"output_tokens":971,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":43461},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[{"input_tokens":3,"output_tokens":971,"cache_read_input_tokens":19384,"cache_creation_input_tokens":43461,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":43461,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"toolStats":{"readCount":1,"searchCount":0,"bashCount":1,"editFileCount":0,"linesAdded":0,"linesRemoved":0,"otherToolCount":0}}}
